Today is the National Day of Remembrance and Action on Violence Against Women, and the day we remember women who had such short lives, but leave such a long legacy. Gender based violence remains a critical issue, in Canada and around the world, and I know that this day I’ll see many women I know mark this day, attend a vigil, appeal to government to keep this issue a priority and good for them. For men who want to be allies, today is a good day to practice.  Violence against women isn’t like rain. It doesn’t come out of nowhere and it is more properly termed “mens violence against women”* and is unlikely to truly change until men who care call out and challenge misogyny where and when they see it. Women can’t change this alone. (*yes. I know. That makes some men really uncomfortable. Buck up. We’re not going to get anywhere with violence against women until we can make it worth at least as much as minor discomfort in men.) #thisisamensissue

Here is a  little reminder that if you’re making cookies this Christmas (or ever) and you need to roll them out to a uniform thickness - your knitting needles make great cookie slats.  You can be as precise as your little heart desires. Let the ends hang over your counter, and then roll. The needles won’t let you roll the dough thinner than they are.  Perfect 4mm cookies. Once again this year we are celebrating Solstice without our customary houseful. Expecting a baby’s arrival during a Covid/flu/RSV surge means another episode of the smallidays for us, and though we know we are doing the right thing, I miss my people and our gatherings most of all this time of year. So - I’m leaning into the things about this night that I love, lighting all our candles, making our annual charitable donations, and have I told you about the kitchen tree? Through the last few years, every time I have felt sadness or found myself casting about for hope, I have put up another strand of twinkle lights, or bought another candle, or strung up another solar string in the garden. (They are out there now, twinkling in the night.) Suddenly this year, one tree didn’t seem like enough, and so I have put up a kitchen tree. It is not a Christmas tree, and I am not going to take it down until I don’t feel a need for it any more. It is a pretty thing in the kitchen, a symbol of the light we all need as we traverse this dark and await the return of the light. Happy Solstice my friends, welcome to winter.

Happy Veganuary! It’s a month where we (vegans everywhere) encourage others to think about giving Veganism a go for the month of January. Our family’s vegan, and I think the biggest barrier to even considering it is that a lot of non-vegans can’t imagine what we eat- so for a few years I’ve been using this month to show you some of our meals as inspiration or illustration. While we’re completely plant based, our reasons for doing so are largely environmental- so while I don’t eat any meat/animal products, I don’t think the whole issue is a zero sum game. Even introducing some vegan meals is helpful, and you don’t have to be perfect to reduce your impact. I’m a day late with this whole thing because there’s a new baby in our house and things are busy, so you can expect some extra simple, fast meals from me. This was tonight’s dinner- pasta with store bought marinara with a little cashew cream added, a simple salad of whatever was in the fridge, and bread stuffed with onion and poppyseed. Delicious, simple, fast, cheap. #veganuary

My son-in-law Alex is not a vegan. As committed to being a vegan as I am, I think that’s sort of how committed he is to not being a vegan. When he’s with us though, he eats vegan- everyone does. (We’re the same way with all dietary stuff - if we had someone gluten-free dining or staying with us we’d all be gluten free while they were here - it seems easiest to go with the lowest common denominator than have a bunch of different meals on the go.) Alex is here to personally vouch that as a non-vegan, this meal (and just about everything he eats with us) is fine and yummy and he has personally never been injured by a vegan meal at all, and he even has a favourite or two, and this is one of them.  A terrific quinoa/lentil “meatloaf” (#linkinbio) and greek lemon potatoes (no recipe, do what I did. Ask someone greek and then sub the chicken stock for veg) and a few steamed veg. Another day, another dinner! Tonight’s a meal that’s on Meg, Alex, Elliot and Joe’s favourites list - Katsu curry.  A warm mild Japanese style curry with breaded slices of extra firm tofu. (In the recipe they fry them, I bake them because I’m lazy, it’s faster, and better for us. I follow the recipe, then pop them in the oven at 220C/425F/Gas Mark 7 until crispy and browned. About 30 min.) While they’re in, the curry comes together quickly and the rice cooks, so doesn’t take too long. We had peas along with, and tomato with balsamic, salt and pepper.  Fast, cheap, nutritious and still gave me lots of baby holding time. #veganuary #welovetofu #linkinbio👆 https://cupfulofkale.com/vegan-tofu-katsu-curry/

Dinner tonight was mostly courtesy of the instant pot and @veganricha’s great recipes. I bought some frozen naan and samosas and we were in business. The whole thing knocked together in about an hour and the only tricky bit was remembering to put the chickpeas to soak this morning. #veganuary #whatveganseat

Busy day, and I almost forgot to post our dinner. Tonight we had “Creamy Tuscan “Chicken” Milanese” (#linkinbio👆) and a Kale salad - more about that one another time, it’s awesome. I’ve made this recipe following it exactly and we like it, but when we sub the “chicken” for the one by @miyokoschinner we love it more. It features tofu, pea protein and  yuba, an ingredient I think is so fun and cool- it’s the skin that forms on soy milk when they heat it. I buy it frozen, it’s yummy and before you trash all over it, remember that cheese is deliberately curdled and aged dairy, arguably much weirder. You’re just used to it. #veganuary #whatveganseat  https://www.rabbitandwolves.com/creamy-tuscan-vegan-chicken-milanese/#recipe

Dinner tonight was a “clean out the fridge” special. A salad with whatever I had along with mint and a quick lemon vinaigrette (that means I shook it together in a jar) a handful of green beans that were leftover from another meal, homemade felafel (so, so much faster and easier than you’re thinking, and I bake rather than fry them) and Koshari - Egypt’s National dish, which just so happens to be vegan. It’s rice, lentils, macaroni and a spiced tomato dish, topped with crispy onions and (usually) chickpeas.  I skipped them because we had the felafel. I know it sounds weird, but you should eat it. Cheap, easy, delicious. If you have a little one in your family I highly recommend mixing in the tomato sauce rather than putting it on top, it will look a little more familiar. Elliot likes it a lot. #veganuary #thingsveganseat

A lovely dinner tonight, fast, delicious and simple. We had a salad with lettuce, radicchio and winter fruit - persimmon and Asian pear. Along with it we had a great pasta - you roast some cherry tomatoes in the oven for a half hour, then cook a little garlic in a pot and add some stock, then dump in your angel hair pasta and 3 minutes later (I swear it is true) the pasta is done and you pitch it in a bowl and dump the cherry tomatoes over the top. There’s a few other bits to it - a little parsley, thyme, etc, but over all it’s a dinner on the table in 30 minutes without a lot of mucking about. Darn tasty too.  I’ve linked the recipe for you in my bio.  #veganuary #whatveganseat #linkinbio👆  https://www.thissavoryvegan.com/creamy-vegan-garlic-pasta/

Behold - Team Abigail. Since Abigail was born three weeks ago, we’ve undertaken something amazing. After Charlotte’s death we made the rather remarkable decision that we’d do whatever it took to feel as safe as possible during the scary first days of Abigails life. I’m sure you can imagine what sort of fears there were. We decided- as a team, that we’d stay awake in shifts and hold Abigail 24 hours a day until we were all (sort of) ready for her to sleep alone. It was a wild decision born out of instinct, and it’s ended up being the most beautiful and lovely time, as we all grew into readiness for the next phase.  Meg, Alex, Ellie and Abigail went home today, feeling as ready as they ever will for their life together. Joe and I miss them already, but feel so proud of them. I wrote about it on the blog #teamabigail #linkinbio https://www.yarnharlot.ca/2023/01/team-abigail/

I had little energy for making supper tonight - I’m itching to start a new sweater and cooking is standing between me and that, so a simple meal was best. This is a sheet pan dinner, of a fashion. You make a quick marinade and brush it all over cauliflower and put it on one pan, and then ingredients for a romesco sauce (red onion, red pepper, garlic) get brushed with the same thing and roasted on another. At the same time, caviar lentils go on the boil.  The boiling and roasting take about 20 minutes, and during that time I put the other ingredients for the sauce in the blender. (Almonds, etc.) When the roasted veg are done, they go in the blender and get whizzed up while I dress and season the lentils, then the whole thing goes on a plate. Oh- and I whacked a handful of green beans on the sheet pan during the last 7 minutes.  Door to door in less than 30 minutes and it’s so delicious and dare I say… fancy!  #veganuary #linkinbio👆 https://www.feastingathome.com/roasted-cauliflower-with-romesco-sauce/

Yesterday, held deep in the thrall of startitis, I broke rule number one in knitting. I didn’t swatch.  I know, I know, I always say swatch and I always even mean it and I can’t explain my own behaviour at all, except to point out that when confronted with the truth about what I had done, I broke rule number two. What rule is that, you may ask? Well, gentle knitter, it is that if something seems wrong it is wrong and you shouldn’t keep knitting hoping that when there’s more knitting it will be less wrong, because that is not how it works. Yet, yesterday I not only didn’t swatch, but when it became obvious that I’d made a mistake, I decided to knit another inch or two on the yoke of this sweater while I thought about what I’d done. Now today, I have knitting ramen and I’m pulling the whole *&%$$#ing thing back.  #ifoughtthelawandthelawwon

Dinner tonight was rice, General Tso’s tofu, carrots and roasted broccoli. Yesterday I spoke a bit about my workflow in the kitchen - how I get this on the table in less than 30 minutes, and here’s how I did tonights.  6:30 - Whisk tofu marinade together (2 ingredients) cut tofu, crank the oven, put rice and water on the boil, peel and slice carrots, cut broccoli. 6:40: carrots on to the stove to cook, broccoli tossed with olive oil and a little salt and set aside. Whisk together sauce ingredients. 6:50: Broccoli in the oven, tofu drained and tossed with cornstarch, popped in a pan to start browning. Garnish cut (scallion and parsley) and salad contemplated and rejected. Handful of cherry tomatoes sliced instead.  7:00: Dump sauce on tofu and stir, plate rice, drain carrots and stir with a little lemon, olive oil and the parsley, retrieve broccoli, toss on plate with tofu on rice, scatter garnish to make me seem fancy and impress Joe - 7:03, dinner on the table. Easy peasy! I’ll toss the tofu recipe in my bio  #veganuary #whatveganseat #linkinbio #eattherainbow  https://simpleveganblog.com/general-tsos-tofu/

Happy Burns night , and a very traditional  menu for our Burns supper. Veg haggis (quite delicious) tatties and neeps in the form of clapshot (potatoes and swede - aka rutabaga- aka scottish turnip, is big with dark skin and yellow flesh, not little like white turnips) with a whiskey sauce, slightly overcooked peas (very on theme) and roasted carrot and parsnip.  Delicious. It was just the two of us tonight so we skipped all the poems but for my favourite “John Anderson My Jo”. On to dessert! #veganuary #whatveganseat

I’ve tried lots of recipes for this, and the one I’m linking in my bio is the best, and easy and fun. You’ll love it. We top it with a little vegan ice cream, but it’s excellent without. After last nights dinner was so rich and so much work, I was ready for a real change of pace tonight. At 6:30 I cranked the oven to 450F (230C, Gas Mark 8) and made a quick sauce in the blender of orange juice, ginger, garlic, peanut butter, soy sauce etc, and then cut some tofu, tossed it with some of that dressing and put it in the oven. I chopped a sweet potato, drizzled it with olive  oil and popped that in too. Then I put my favourite rice combo in the instant pot (brown rice, barley, black rice) and set it for 15 minutes.  While the rice cooked and the tofu and and potato roasted, I chopped some pre-cook beets, sliced some snap peas, carrots and red cabbage, and fetched some sunflower sprouts from the fridge. When the rice was done the tofu and potatoes were too, and I whacked it all on a plate, added a bit more of the dressing from the blender, and ate it. 25 minutes from opening the fridge to food on the table with lots for tomorrow’s lunches too. #eattherainbow🌈 #veganuary #whatveganseat #linkinbio👆 https://www.feastingathome.com/bali-bowls-with-peanut-tofu/

Dinner tonight? I thought you’d never ask. We had rice with cumin seeds and peas, sliced tomatoes, cabbage cooked with mustard seeds and coconut, and Rajma. Rajma is an Indian kidney bean curry (though like channa masala or lots of other “curries” it doesn’t have curry powder) that’s terrific. I cook it in the instant pot from dried beans and I spend a little time at the beginning chopping onion and garlic and measuring spices, but after a few minutes it’s cooking away, completely unattended with delicious result. It’s a super tasty, nutritious, cheap and approachable Indian dish you should come to know and love. Elliot ate a big portion of everything tonight, though prefers his cabbage raw and had some while I prepped dinner. I use dried beans and tinned tomato (usually, today I had three dodgy fresh ones I need to use up) and together with the pantry coconut, cheap cabbage and frozen peas,  I think this is the least expensive meal I know how to make.  #whatveganseat #veganuary #linkinbio👆 https://www.veganricha.com/quick-rajma-red-kidney-beans-curry/

I have a warp on this loom long enough to weave two little towels and a matching washcloth. If you were to run to your washroom right now and look at your towels, you’d likely see that they’ve got a hem that’s a bit of folded and sewn fabric that’s not fluffy, and that’s the bit I have to weave between each item on the loom. I start by weaving a bit of tape, using the warp yarn for the weft as well, then weave the towel, then weave tape - a bit of waste (the dark green) that’s where I’ll cut them apart, and then more tape to start the next thing. When all this comes off the loom, those bits of tape will be sewn to be the hems.  Almost done now!

It is with great sadness that I write to tell you that Suzanne Pederson -mother, grandmother, the  powerhouse behind Madrona Fiber Arts and my sweet friend, died yesterday morning, the 2nd of March, just days short of her 80th birthday. Suzanne had an unwavering ability to create community in the textile world, and her legacy is one of learning, charity, friendship and connection. Before large-format fibre events were a thing, there was Madrona, and her vision for that event changed our concept of how knitters, weavers and spinners could gather and launched careers. To work for her was one of the great honours of my career, and earning her friendship one of my greatest treasures. So many of us can trace our greatest relationships, both personal and professional, back to her remarkable launchpad. While her talents were many, her energy boundless and her tenacity legendary, I can tell you that her ability to see right through people and situations was supernatural. She always knew what was going on, and those of us who loved her knew that her phone number was the best thing you could have in any crisis. Suzanne’s solutions and advice were always miraculously kind, clever, and creative. She leaves a remarkable wake in her passing, and I will miss her deeply.  Bon Voyage, darling Suzanne.

The Vibes Tee is knit in four colours, but I’m knitting it in three, so some decisions needed to be made - Do I combine stripes or make two stripes the same colour? What colour? What stripes? Last night I’d decided to make the two wide stripes blue and white, and use the coral as the accent for both the skinny stripes. Then I considered combining the first and second stripes, so the wide stripes would still be blue and white, but there would only be one skinny stripe of coral in each set, rather than two. I thought that was the answer. Then this morning I got up and decided (before coffee) that coral and blue should be my main colours, with a skinny stripe of white, and then I cast on and knit the first stripe with coral even though the entire time I was knitting it every stitch was regret. What do you think? Rip it? Keep it? What should the plan be? Why didn’t I make a better plan yesterday? Why do knitters deny their instincts? Why can’t we be trusted around stripes? Should I just go try to ride 60km and then think about it? I’m going with that last one, but I’m going to think about this the whole time.  #badstarttoaKAL #StrungalongKAL #vibestee

You were all right of course, and if I’ve learned anything it’s that you should stop knitting the minute you think “well that’s not right” instead of charging on hoping you can outknit the problem. The coral was still coral when I got back from my bike ride (even though I was gone a really long time) so I ripped and restarted and I feel better already. strungalongkal #vibestee

My mum died six years ago today - and once I was through the shock of it, I started trying to turn this day into a family holiday to observe, rather than a day of just grief and sorrow. In todays knitting news, I have once again hung in there way, way too long hoping that knitting something longer would make it wider. Pro-tip: It never does.  I tried this sweater on right after I divided the arms and body and it was a hair tighter than I like. *I gave it a tug and told myself blocking would fix it, and knit another chunk. It was still sort of looking a bit small to me, so I put the body on a cord and tried it on again. It was still a smidge snug, so I repeated from *. Now I’m just about to start the ribbing and for some crazy reason it’s still the same width it was when I started (I KNOW SO WEIRD RIGHT?) So… I blocked it. Predictably, blocking changed nothing and while I thought about that while I added another inch, hoping once again that would fix it. Now I’m getting ready to rip the whole thing back to the divide because even though I have been knitting for 51 years and making something longer has never made it wider, I tried again just to make sure.  I’m thinking about starting a different sweater.
I absolutely ripped that sweater all the way back to the divide, and now I’m (slightly bitterly) knitting my way back down. The urge to cast on something different is a minute to minute  struggle.

It’s Thanksgiving weekend and I have so much to do, so much to cook, but the very first thing I always make is the cranberry sauce. It’s so pretty, the berries bursting in the pan is fun, it makes the house smell festive, and it reminds me of my mum.  Here is how I make it. I put one package of cranberries in a pot and check for yucky ones. (Take those out.) Add 3/4 cup white sugar and 1/4 cup brown sugar.  Zest an orange and put that in, and then juice the orange and put it in a measuring cup, and add as much water as it takes to make a cup. Put it on the heat and bring to a boil, then turn the heat down and bubble for about 15 minutes, That’s it. Happy Thanksgiving, or Christmas, or whenever you like to have it.

Hey! It’s Veganuary! It’s a month meant to encourage people to think about giving veganism a go for the month of January. Our family’s diet is plant based, and I think a big barrier for folks is that they can’t imagine what might be for dinner if they took meat out, so this month I’ll show you how we do it.  While what we all choose to eat is complex and has to do with so many factors (culture, opportunity, choices) being vegan is more sustainable, cheaper, better for my health, and fewer creatures suffer for my pleasure, and all those things together feel great to me. The best thing about veganuary is that thinking about becoming vegan or even enjoying some plant based meals in your rotation isn’t a zero-sum game. Doing it a little is better than not doing it at all - you don’t have to be all plant based all the time to make a difference, it’s kinda like deciding to ride your bike some of the time. Another day I wasn’t totally feeling dinner, but I committed to a 20 min effort and here we are. Inspired by the recipe I’ll link to in my profile, I stood in front of the fridge for a few minutes and looked at what I had. 3 mushrooms, a dodgy bit of kale, a few cherry tomatoes about to give it up, some broccoli from yesterday… and frozen diced butternut squash. I cranked the oven to 230C/450F/Gas mark 8, and tossed the mushrooms and broccoli with a bit of oil and popped it on a sheet, then tossed the frozen squash, a rough chopped shallot and a whole garlic clove with a little oil and curry powder and whacked it in the oven on the same sheet. Into the blender I put a small tin of coconut milk (160ml) and a spoon of red curry paste, and a small knob of ginger. When the veg were done (about 12 min) I tossed the squash mix in the blender too, and ran everything until it was smooth. I used that 12 min to toss some chickpeas in a pan until they were kinda crispy, and boiled water for a single serving pack of udon noodles. When everything was done, all the veg went into the base along with enough veg broth to make it soupy, then I put the noodles in a bowl and topped them with everything else, and cilantro because Joe is still gone, and while I did that, I warmed a frozen naan bread in the oven. Whabam. #veganuary #whatveganseatwhentheywanttoorderin https://www.thissavoryvegan.com/butternut-squash-curry-noodle-soup/

This months Self Imposed Sock Club socks continue to trot along, I’m halfway through the heel flaps - this 10 rounds a day thing is working so far. My instinct told me that 10 a day would work, but today my curiosity won out over my desire to avoid all mathematics, and I did some figuring. Would 10 rounds a day (per sock) really yield a pair of socks in a month? Less than 300 rounds? I added it up. 20 rounds for the ribbing, 72 for the leg. 32 for the heel flap (I counted rows as rounds because why not) and 17 for the gusset. Around 70 for the foot, 24 for the toe and that my little butterflies, adds up to 235. (Probably ) That means that even if these were socks for someone with bigger feet, I have an extra 45 rounds to throw around, so yup 10 rounds a day will get you a sock. Shazam.

Once every #veganuary I try to give you an easy, cheap, fast and delicious meal you can put in your regular rotation- and tonight’s dinner is all that and more. It’s an all-time favourite of Elliots, and is super kid-friendly. Based roughly on the idea of pasta e ceci (pasta with chickpeas) Do this:  mince four cloves of garlic and sauté in some olive oil (maybe a tablespoon?) for a couple of minutes in your favourite pot. After 2 or three minutes, dump in a can of tomato paste (one the little ones) and cook that stirring all around for several minutes until the paste is  a darker shade of red.  Drain a can of chickpeas (540ml/19oz) and dump them in, then add about a cup and a half of a small pasta. We like ditali - and then toss in a couple cans worth of water and a bit of salt. Bring it up to a simmer, and cook, stirring frequently (sometimes the pasta tries to stick to the bottom) and adding more water if you need to, until the pasta is done, most of the water is absorbed and boom, you’re done. Taste, season, and serve. 20 min- about $4 in ingredients, and serves two adults and two littles. (Depending on appetites, Elliot will eat his body weight of this one.) Enjoy, enjoy. #whatveganseat
